Example:

Assume 3 clients:

Client A → OPEN
Client B → CLOSED
Client C → OPEN

Loop execution:

A → message sent ✅
B → return ❌
C → never reached

Result:

Only first client receives message.

Using continue:

function broadcast(wss, payload) {
    for (const client of wss.clients) {

        if (client.readyState !== WebSocket.OPEN)
            continue;

        client.send(JSON.stringify(payload));
    }
}

Execution:

A → send ✅
B → skip ⏭️
C → send ✅

Result:

All open clients receive messages.

Difference:

return   → stop entire function
continue → skip current iteration only
break    → stop loop but remain inside function

For WebSocket broadcasting, continue is usually the correct choice because one disconnected client should not block everyone else.

You could also reuse your helper and make it cleaner:

function broadcast(wss, payload) {
    for (const client of wss.clients) {
        sendJson(client, payload);
    }
}

because sendJson() already checks:

if (socket.readyState !== WebSocket.OPEN) return;

That avoids duplicating the same condition.


