or PASTE THIS IN CONSOLE. 
const ws = new WebSocket("ws://localhost:8080/ws");

ws.onopen = () => {
  console.log("CONNECTED");
};

ws.onmessage = (event) => {
  console.log("MESSAGE:", event.data);
};

ws.onclose = (event) => {
  console.log(
    "CLOSED",
    event.code,
    event.reason
  );
};

ws.onerror = (err) => {
  console.log("ERROR", err);
};

OUTPUT :
CONNECTED
VM76:8 MESSAGE: {"type":"welcome"}





wscat -c ws://localhost:8080/ws

1. Start your server

Terminal:

npm run dev

Expected:

Server is running on http://localhost:8080
Websocket Server is running on ws://localhost:8080/ws
2. Open the browser

Go to:

http://localhost:8080

You should see:

Hello from express server

Do not open:

http://localhost:8080/ws

That endpoint is not a webpage.

3. Open Developer Tools

Chrome:

Right click → Inspect → Console
4. Connect to WebSocket

Paste this in Console:

const ws = new WebSocket("ws://localhost:8080/ws");

ws.onopen = () => {
  console.log("CONNECTED");
};

ws.onmessage = (event) => {
  console.log("MESSAGE:", event.data);
};

ws.onclose = (event) => {
  console.log(
    "CLOSED",
    event.code,
    event.reason
  );
};

ws.onerror = (err) => {
  console.log("ERROR", err);
};

Expected:

CONNECTED
MESSAGE: {"type":"welcome"}
5. Trigger a broadcast

Open Thunder Client and send:

POST http://localhost:8080/matches

Body:

{
  "sport": "football",
  "homeTeam": "Manchester City",
  "awayTeam": "JSM United",
  "startTime": "2026-06-16T09:00:00.000Z",
  "endTime": "2026-06-16T11:00:00.000Z"
}

Browser console should receive:

MESSAGE:
{
  "type":"match_created",
  "data": { ... }
}

That confirms:

Express works ✅
WebSocket connects ✅
Broadcast works ✅


